# Practice Workflow

## Purpose

The Practice Workflow defines how a musician interacts with Practice with Purpose during a typical practice session.

The workflow is intentionally designed around how musicians naturally practice rather than around software workflows.

The application should adapt to the musician—not require the musician to adapt to the application.

A musician should be able to begin practicing within five seconds of opening the application.

---

# Core Principles

Every practice session should be:

- Easy to start
- Flexible
- Non-restrictive
- Focused
- Encouraging

The application should never interrupt the natural flow of practice.

Practice decisions remain under the musician's control at all times.

---

# The Practice Journey

Every practice session follows the same general flow.

```
Open Application

↓

Choose Music

↓

Practice

↓

Review

↓

Finish
```

The application quietly supports the musician throughout this process without requiring unnecessary interaction.

---

# Home

The Home screen should immediately answer one question:

> **What should I practice today?**

The screen presents:

- Resume Your Progress
- Recent Pieces
- Add Piece
- Teacher Assignments (if available)
- Recommended Focus (if available)

The application should never require the user to complete setup before beginning practice.

---

# Choosing Music

The musician chooses the piece they wish to practice.

This may be:

- Continuing an existing work
- Beginning a new work
- Opening a teacher assignment
- Selecting a personal practice piece

Selecting a piece opens its Piece Dashboard.

---

# Piece Dashboard

The Piece Dashboard serves as the central hub for that musical work.

It contains:

- Practice history
- Progress over time
- Teacher assignments
- Practice recommendations
- Previous recordings
- Practice heat map
- Start Practice

The dashboard should answer:

> **Where am I with this piece?**

without overwhelming the musician with unnecessary statistics.

---

# Starting Practice

Beginning a practice session should require only a single action.

Selecting **Start Practice** opens the Practice Workspace.

No setup wizard is required.

The application should automatically restore sensible defaults such as:

- previous practice location
- previous zoom level
- previous score position

These defaults should always remain editable.

---

# Practice Workspace

The Practice Workspace is the heart of the application.

Everything needed during practice remains visible throughout the session.

The workspace includes:

- Sheet music
- Recording controls
- Practice timer
- Current passage
- Practice focus
- Session goals
- Recording history
- Practice observations

The musician should never have to leave this workspace while practicing.

---

# Practice Timer

A practice session begins when the musician enters the Practice Workspace.

The application records the total practice time.

The timer may optionally include a user-defined target duration.

Example:

20 minute session

The timer is intended to encourage consistent practice—not create pressure.

---

# Choosing a Focus

Practice Focus tells the application what the musician would like additional feedback on.

Examples include:

- Intonation
- Rhythm
- Dynamics
- Technique
- Musical Expression
- Performance Preparation
- Warm-up
- Learn New Material

Selecting a focus does not limit the analysis.

The application continues evaluating all measurable aspects of the performance while emphasizing the selected focus.

Focus may be changed at any time.

---

# Choosing a Passage

The musician may practice:

- entire piece
- movement
- selected measures
- any custom passage

Changing the passage never ends or restarts the practice session.

The application should support practicing in whatever order the musician chooses.

---

# Practice Goals

Goals are optional.

Examples include:

- Practice for 20 minutes
- Three successful repetitions
- Reach target tempo
- Teacher assignment
- Custom goal

Goals exist to encourage deliberate practice.

They never prevent the musician from continuing.

---

# Recording

Recording is available at any time.

Each recording becomes part of the current practice session.

Recordings represent the learning process rather than polished performances.

The application preserves this history to better understand long-term improvement.

Recordings may be removed only when they are accidental or invalid recordings.

---

# Analysis

Analysis occurs automatically after a recording has been completed.

The application evaluates measurable aspects of the performance including:

- Intonation
- Rhythm
- Timing
- Dynamics
- Tempo consistency
- Technical patterns

The application should avoid assigning a single overall score.

Its purpose is understanding—not grading.

---

# Practice Guidance

Rather than presenting grades, the application visualizes practice priorities.

The score gradually becomes a practice map.

Examples:

Green
Comfortable

Yellow
Needs reinforcement

Red
Recommended focus

The purpose of these visual indicators is to answer:

> **Where should I spend my next few minutes?**

Color represents practice priority—not musical ability.

---

# Practice Continues

Practice is intentionally flexible.

At any time the musician may:

- record again
- change passage
- change focus
- change goals
- replay recordings
- continue practicing

Nothing should interrupt the natural flow of practice.

---

# Practice Summary

Ending a practice session presents a summary of learning rather than a report card.

The summary includes:

Practice Time

Number of Recordings

Areas that improved

Areas that still need attention

Suggested focus for the next session

Example:

Today's Practice

22 minutes

Measures 23–25

Rhythm became noticeably more consistent.

Intonation improved throughout the session.

Tomorrow, continue working on the shift into Measure 24.

Estimated practice time:
8–10 minutes.

The summary should always leave the musician encouraged to continue practicing.

---

# Returning Tomorrow

Every practice session is independent.

The application never resumes yesterday's session.

Instead it builds upon previous learning.

The Home screen should simply suggest where the musician may wish to begin.

Practice always starts fresh.

---

# Teacher Assignments (Future)

When connected to a teacher account, assignments appear naturally within the workflow.

The student remains free to choose another practice activity at any time.

Teacher assignments guide practice but never prevent personal exploration.

---

# Design Goals

Every step in this workflow should reinforce the following principles:

- A musician should be able to begin practicing within five seconds.
- The application should never interrupt the flow of practice.
- The musician always remains in control.
- Recommendations should guide—not dictate.
- Practice sessions celebrate learning rather than perfection.
- The application should visualize priorities rather than grades.
- Every interaction should leave the musician more motivated to practice tomorrow.
